# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: freertos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] An **embedded operating system** (**EOS**) is an operating system designed specifically for embedded computer systems.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] These systems aim to enhance functionality and reliability to perform dedicated tasks.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] When the multitasking method employed allows for timely task execution, such an OS may qualify as a real-time operating system (RTOS).
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Embedded operating systems are integral to consumer electronics such as cameras and mobile phones.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Additionally, they power automotive electronics, aiding in functions like cruise control and navigation.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Moreover, they are essential for factory automation infrastructure.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Everyday applications of EOS include office automation devices such as image scanners, photocopiers, and wireless access points.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Home automation systems, including security systems, also depend on EOS.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Embedded systems comprise a processor and corresponding software.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Embedded software requires storage for executables and temporary data processing during runtime.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Embedded systems typically utilize ROM and RAM as main memory components.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] For functionality, embedded systems necessitate input and output interfaces.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Embedded hardware configurations are often unique, varying according to the application.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Given the resource limitations of embedded system hardware, operating systems are designed with a narrow scope, tailored to specific applications to ensure optimal operation within hardware constraints.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] The choice of embedded operating system, which organizes and controls the hardware, often dictates the additional required embedded hardware components.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Software developers might write essential code in assembly language to harness the full processing power of the central processing unit (CPU).
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Assembly language, being *machine-efficient,* can enhance speed in deterministic systems but may reduce portability and maintainability.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Frequently, embedded operating systems are coded in portable programming languages like C.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] The concept of a real-time multitasking kernel emerged in the late 1970s.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] During the 1980s, as embedded systems applications grew in complexity, operating systems with real-time multitasking kernels struggled to meet the evolving demands of embedded development.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] This led to the evolution of the real-time multitasking kernel into a comprehensive operating system (RTOS), encompassing networking, file management, development, and debugging capabilities.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Today, RTOS constitutes a global industry.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] In 1981, Ready System developed VRTX32, the world’s first commercial embedded real-time kernel.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] In 1993, following a merger, Ready System and Silicon Valley’s Microtec Research developed two new RTOS kernels, VRTX32 and VRTXsa, building upon VRTXmc.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Concurrently, the VRTX integrated development environment, Spectra, was introduced.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] In 1996, Microsoft released its embedded operating system, WinCE, which supported various processor architectures including x86, ARM, SH4, and MIPS.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] WinCE has since become obsolete, with mainstream support having ended in 2018.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] OS-9 and VxWorks are also notable embedded operating systems.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] In the current landscape of the internet of things (IoT), embedded devices are ubiquitous, with cars alone utilizing hundreds of sensors.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] IoT systems, in contrast to traditional embedded systems, necessitate lower power consumption, enhanced safety and reliability, and the capability for ad hoc networking .
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] The communication layer must facilitate the conversion between diverse protocols, while the application layer should enable cloud computing capabilities over the Internet.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] As a result, several new embedded operating systems have gained popularity, such as embedded Linux variants (OpenWrt, Zeroshell, Android, LineageOS, LEDE, LibreCMC), OpenHarmony, Oniro OS, HarmonyOS, NetBSD, PX5 RTOS, ThreadX, FreeRTOS, SEGGER embOS, Tock, Windows IoT among others.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Numerous Linux-based projects, toolkits, and frameworks have been developed for creating operating systems that operate on a variety of embedded systems.
[src:freertos/embedded-operating-system] Prominent examples of these include OpenEmbedded, BusyBox, uClibc, musl libc, and Buildroot.
[src:freertos/freertos] The FreeRTOS kernel was originally developed by Richard Barry around 2003, and was later developed and maintained by Barry's company, Real Time Engineers Ltd.
[src:freertos/freertos] In 2017, the firm passed stewardship of the FreeRTOS project to Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:freertos/freertos] Barry continues to work on FreeRTOS as part of an AWS team.
[src:freertos/freertos] With the transition to Amazon control, subsequent releases of the project also switched licensing from GPL version 2 (with special exceptions for static linking to proprietary code outside the FreeRTOS kernel itself) to MIT.
[src:freertos/freertos] FreeRTOS is designed to be small and simple.
[src:freertos/freertos] It is mostly written in the C programming language to make it easy to port and maintain.
[src:freertos/freertos] It also comprises a few assembly language functions where needed, mostly in architecture-specific context-switching routines used by the scheduler.
[src:freertos/freertos] FreeRTOS provides methods for multiple threads or tasks, mutexes, semaphores and software timers.
[src:freertos/freertos] A tickless mode is provided for low power applications.
[src:freertos/freertos] RTOSes typically do not have the more advanced features that are found in operating systems like Linux and Microsoft Windows, such as device drivers, advanced memory management, and user accounts.
[src:freertos/freertos] The emphasis is on compactness and speed of execution.
[src:freertos/freertos] FreeRTOS can be thought of as a thread library rather than an operating system, although command line interface and POSIX-like input/output (I/O) abstraction are available.
[src:freertos/freertos] FreeRTOS implements multiple threads by having the host program call a thread tick method at regular short intervals.
[src:freertos/freertos] The thread tick method switches tasks depending on priority and a round-robin scheduling scheme.
[src:freertos/freertos] The usual interval is 1 to 10 milliseconds (1⁄1000 to 1⁄100 of a second) via an interrupt from a hardware timer, but this interval is often changed to suit a given application.
[src:freertos/freertos] The software distribution contains prepared configurations and demonstrations for every port and compiler, allowing rapid application design.
[src:freertos/freertos] The project website provides documentation and RTOS tutorials, and details of the RTOS design.
[src:freertos/freertos] Amazon provides a now deprecated extension of FreeRTOS, this is FreeRTOS with libraries for Internet of things (IoT) support, specifically for Amazon Web Services.
[src:freertos/freertos] Since version 10.0.0 in 2017, Amazon has taken stewardship of the FreeRTOS code, including any updates to the original kernel.
[src:freertos/freertos] SAFERTOS was developed as a complementary version of FreeRTOS, with common functions, but designed for safety-critical implementation.
[src:freertos/freertos] FreeRTOS was subject to hazard and operability study (HAZOP), and weaknesses were identified and resolved.
[src:freertos/freertos] The result was put through a full IEC 61508 SIL 3 development lifecycle, the highest level for a software-only component.
[src:freertos/freertos] SAFERTOS was developed by Wittenstein High Integrity Systems, in partnership with Real Time Engineers Ltd, primary developer of the FreeRTOS project.
[src:freertos/freertos] Both SAFERTOS and FreeRTOS share the same scheduling algorithm, have similar application programming interfaces (APIs), and are otherwise very similar, but they were developed with differing objectives.
[src:freertos/freertos] SAFERTOS was developed solely in the C language to meet requirements for certification to IEC61508.
[src:freertos/freertos] SAFERTOS can reside solely in the on-chip read-only memory (ROM) of a microcontroller for standards compliance.
[src:freertos/freertos] When implemented in hardware memory, SAFERTOS code can only be used in its original, certified configuration.
[src:freertos/freertos] This means certifying a system needs no retesting of the kernel portion of a design.
[src:freertos/freertos] SAFERTOS is included in the ROM of some Stellaris Microcontrollers from Texas Instruments.
[src:freertos/freertos] SAFERTOS source code does not need to be separately purchased.
[src:freertos/freertos] In this usage scenario, a C header file is used to map SAFERTOS API functions to their location in read-only memory.
[src:freertos/freertos] OPENRTOS is a commercially licensed version of Amazon FreeRTOS, sold by Wittenstein High Integrity Systems.
[src:freertos/freertos] This product provides support and allows companies to use the Amazon FreeRTOS kernel and libraries under the terms of a commercial license instead of the MIT open source license.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks supports AMD/Intel architecture, POWER architecture, ARM architectures, and RISC-V.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The RTOS can be used in multicore asymmetric multiprocessing (AMP), symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), and mixed modes and multi-OS (via Type 1 hypervisor) designs on 32- and 64-bit processors.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks comes with the kernel, middleware, board support packages, Wind River Workbench development suite, complementary third-party software and hardware.
[src:freertos/vxworks] In its latest release, VxWorks 7, the RTOS has been re-engineered for modularity and upgradeability so the OS kernel is separate from middleware, applications, and other packages.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Scalability, security, safety, connectivity, and graphics have been improved to address Internet of Things (IOT) needs.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks started in the late 1980s as a set of enhancements to a simple RTOS called VRTX sold by Ready Systems (becoming a Mentor Graphics product in 1995).
[src:freertos/vxworks] Wind River acquired rights to distribute VRTX and significantly enhanced it by adding, among other things, a file system and an integrated development environment.
[src:freertos/vxworks] In 1987, anticipating the termination of its reseller contract by Ready Systems, Wind River proceeded to develop its own kernel to replace VRTX within VxWorks.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Published in 2003 with a Wind River copyright, "Real-Time Concepts for Embedded Systems" describes the development environment, runtime setting, and system call families of the RTOS.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Written by Wind River employees with a foreword by Jerry Fiddler, chairman, and co-founder of Wind River, the textbook is an excellent tutorial on the RTOS.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks supports Intel architecture, Power architecture, and ARM architectures.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The RTOS can be used in multi-core asymmetric multiprocessing (AMP), symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), mixed modes and multi-OS (via Type 1 hypervisor) designs on 32- and 64- bit processors.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The VxWorks consists of a set of runtime components and development tools.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks core development tools are compilers such as Diab, GNU, and Intel C++ Compiler (ICC) and its build and configuration tools.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The system also includes productivity tools such as its Workbench development suite and Intel tools and development support tools for asset tracking and host support.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The platform is a modular, vendor-neutral, open system that supports a range of third-party software and hardware.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The OS kernel is separate from middleware, applications, and other packages, which enables easier bug fixes and testing of new features.
[src:freertos/vxworks] An implementation of a layered source build system allows multiple versions of any stack to be installed at the same time so developers can select which version of any feature set should go into the VxWorks kernel libraries.
[src:freertos/vxworks] In March 2014 Wind River introduced VxWorks 7, emphasizing scalability, security, safety, connectivity, graphics, and virtualization.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The following lists some of the release 7 updates.
[src:freertos/vxworks] More information can be found on the Wind Rivers VxWorks website.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks has been ported to a number of platforms.
[src:freertos/vxworks] This includes the Intel x86 family (including the Intel Quark SoC), MIPS, PowerPC (and BAE RAD), Freescale ColdFire, Intel i960, SPARC, Fujitsu FR-V, SH-4 and the closely related family of ARM, StrongARM and xScale CPUs.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks provides a standard board support package (BSP) interface between all its supported hardware and the OS.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Wind River's BSP developer kit provides a common application programming interface (API) and a stable environment for real-time operating system development.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks is supported by popular SSL/TLS libraries such as wolfSSL.
[src:freertos/vxworks] As is common in embedded system development, cross-compiling is used with VxWorks.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Development is done on a "host" system where an integrated development environment (IDE), including the editor, compiler toolchain, debugger, and emulator can be used.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Software is then compiled to run on the "target" system.
[src:freertos/vxworks] This allows the developer to work with powerful development tools while targeting more limited hardware.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks supports a range of target architectures including ARM, Intel, Power architecture, RISC-V architecture and more.
[src:freertos/vxworks] For the latest target architecture processors and board support packages, refer to the VxWorks Marketplace or via citation.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The Eclipse-based Workbench IDE that comes with VxWorks is used to configure, analyze, optimize, and debug a VxWorks-based system under development.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The *Tornado* IDE was used for VxWorks 5.x and was replaced by the Eclipse-based *Workbench* IDE for VxWorks 6.x. and later.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Workbench is also the IDE for the Wind River Linux, On-Chip Debugging, and Wind River Diab Compiler product lines.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks 7 uses Wind River Workbench 4 which updates to the Eclipse 4 base provides full third party plug-in support and usability improvements.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Wind River Simics is a standalone simulation tool compatible with VxWorks.
[src:freertos/vxworks] It simulates the full target system (hardware and software) to create a shared platform for software development.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Multiple developers can share a complete virtual system and its entire state, including execution history.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Simics enables early and continuous system integration and faster prototyping by utilizing virtual prototypes instead of physical prototypes.
[src:freertos/vxworks] VxWorks is used by products across a wide range of market areas: aerospace and defense, automotive, industrial such as robots, consumer electronics, medical area and networking.
[src:freertos/vxworks] Several notable products also use VxWorks as the onboard operating system.
[src:freertos/vxworks] As of July 2019, a paper published by Armis exposed 11 critical vulnerabilities, including remote code execution, denial of service, information leaks, and logical flaws impacting more than two billion devices using the VxWorks RTOS.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The vulnerability allows attackers to tunnel into an *internal* network using the vulnerability and hack into printers, laptops, and any other connected devices.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The vulnerability can bypass firewalls as well.
[src:freertos/vxworks] The system is in use by quite a few mission-critical products, many of which could not be easily patched.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] It is named after Zephyrus, the ancient Greek god of the west wind.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Zephyr originated from Virtuoso RTOS for digital signal processors (DSPs).
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] In 2001, Wind River Systems acquired Belgian software company Eonic Systems, the developer of Virtuoso.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] In November 2015, Wind River Systems renamed the operating system to *Rocket*, made it open-source and royalty-free.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Compared to Wind River's other RTOS, VxWorks, Rocket had much smaller memory needs, especially suitable for sensors and single-function embedded devices.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Rocket could fit into as little as 4 KB of memory, while VxWorks needed 200 KB or more.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] In February 2016, Rocket became a hosted collaborative project of the Linux Foundation under the name *Zephyr*.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Wind River Systems contributed the Rocket kernel to Zephyr, but still provided Rocket to its clients, charging them for the cloud services.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] As a result, Rocket became "essentially the commercial version of Zephyr".
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Since then, early members and supporters of Zephyr include Intel, NXP Semiconductors, Synopsys, Linaro, Texas Instruments, Nordic Semiconductor, Oticon, and Bose.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] As of January 2025, Zephyr had the largest number of contributors and commits compared to other RTOSes (including Mbed, RT-Thread, NuttX, and RIOT).
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Zephyr intends to provide all components needed to develop resource-constrained and embedded or microcontroller-based applications.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Zephyr uses Kconfig and devicetree as its configuration systems, inherited from the Linux kernel, but implemented in Python programming language for portability to non-Unix operating systems.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] The RTOS build system is based on CMake, which allows Zephyr applications to be built on Linux, macOS, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Zephyr has a general-purpose tool called *West* for managing repositories, downloading programs to hardware, etc.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Early Zephyr kernels used a dual nanokernel plus microkernel design.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] In December 2016, with Zephyr 1.6, this changed to a monolithic kernel.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] A group is dedicated to maintaining and improving the security.
[src:freertos/zephyr-operating-system] Also, being owned and supported by a community means the world's open source developers are vetting the code, which significantly increases security.
[src:freertos/μclinux] After the mainline merge, the μClinux project continued to develop patches and tools for microcontrollers.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The last Wayback Machine archive of the homepage (from 2018) lists Linux kernel releases for 2.0, 2.4 and 2.6 (all of which are end-of-life in mainline, 2.6 being the last to go in 2016), with the last news entry dated May 2016 concerning a new release of the kernel distribution.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The website remained unchanged through 2021, when it went offline.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The letters "μC" are for "microcontroller": the name is pronounced "you-see-Linux", rather than pronouncing the letter mu as in Greek.
[src:freertos/μclinux] Jeff Dionne and Kenneth Albanowski in 1998.
[src:freertos/μclinux] Initially, they targeted the Motorola DragonBall family of embedded 68k processors (specifically the 68EZ328 series used in the 3Com PalmPilot) on a 2.0.33 Linux kernel.
[src:freertos/μclinux] After releasing their initial work, a developer community quickly sprang up extending their work to newer kernels and other microprocessor architectures.
[src:freertos/μclinux] In early 1999, support was added for the Motorola (now NXP) ColdFire family of embedded microprocessors.
[src:freertos/μclinux] Although originally targeting 2.0 series Linux kernels, it now has ports based on Linux 2.4 and Linux 2.6.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The Linux 2.4 ports were forward ported from the 2.0.36 Linux kernel by Michael Leslie and Evan Stawnyczy during their work at Rt-Control.
[src:freertos/μclinux] There were never any μClinux extensions applied to the 2.2 series kernels.
[src:freertos/μclinux] Since version 2.5.46 of the Linux kernel, the major parts of μClinux have been integrated with the mainline kernel for a number of processor architectures.
[src:freertos/μclinux] Greg Ungerer (who originally ported μClinux to the Motorola ColdFire family of processors) continued to maintain and actively push core μClinux support into the 2.6 series Linux kernels.
[src:freertos/μclinux] In this regard, μClinux is essentially no longer a separate fork of Linux.
[src:freertos/μclinux] μClinux had support for many architectures, and forms the basis of many products, like network routers, security cameras, DVD or MP3 players, VoIP phone or gateways, scanners, and card readers.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The volume of mails on the μClinux mailing list greatly decreased in the 2010s, with very few months producing more than 100 KB of mail in total.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The Linux kernel upstream marked version 2.6 as end-of-life in February 2016.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The last "uclinux-dist", a distribution package containing the source code of the patched kernel, was released on SourceForge September 2016.
[src:freertos/μclinux] It contained not only 2.6 but also those based on newer upstream versions 3.x and 4.x.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The last update of most tools on SourceForge also date back to February and September 2016.
[src:freertos/μclinux] Support for several of the original target architectures was dropped in April 2018 by the Linux upstream.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The obsolete CPU architectures set to be removed in Linux 4.17 and subsequent releases included ADI Blackfin, Etrax CRIS, Fujitsu FR-V, Mitsubishi M32R, Matsushita/Panasonic MN10300, Imagination META (Metag), and Tilera TILE.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The homepage was last seen updated in 2018 per Wayback Machine.
[src:freertos/μclinux] Tools for arm-linux-gnueabi and mips64 were updated in 2018.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The last accessible archives of the project's website date to 2021.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The website presumably went offline after this point.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The GitHub page of the project continued to receive occasional updates, with the elf2flt tool last updated in August 2024.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The SourceForge page was last updated in 2023, a with new tool build for m68k.
[src:freertos/μclinux] The leanXCam was an open-source programmable smart camera used for industrial applications in the field of machine vision that ran under μClinux; the camera won an award at the 2008 VISION tradeshow.
[src:freertos/μclinux] As of 2015, the project was discontinued.
